Leibniz says every "created substance" exercises a physical influence on every single other physical substance (e.g. gravity of the atoms on the other end of the cosmos, "butterfly effect", the zodiac, etc.), but no created substance exercises metaphysical influence on any other.

He says things "only transform" and never come into or out of existence, which seems sort of tame as an idea, but it's also the logic behind the bodies of saints not rotting and us venerating their relics - it's literally them. Also vacuum is contradiction-in-terms, thus Aether.

When you read a 20th century text and see the word "bourgeoise", if the author is a right-winger, you should read it as "normies", and if the author is a leftist, you should read it as "white people". That way it will be linguistically correct in a way you can actually understand

Like just reading Julius Evola's social critique on how people get into empty relationships based on socializing or waste their time with bullshit it's obvious he's trying to call them "normies" but /r9k/ didn't invent the word yet so he's stuck with more primitive language tools

Also any communist talking about middle class, bourgeoise, etc. wants to wipe out white people, but like he's writing in Europe before they invented minorities there so he had to get creative and come up with fake economical distinctions as a place-holder before Kalergiing it up.

Very interesting 17th century case of a woman with rheumatism pains in the hip, who was cured by taking cold baths every day for a month in summer. The second bath, the pain "fell" down to the foot, third time it disappeared.

Writer says she also had a breast tumor that was probably cancer and during the first day's cold bath it hurt horribly, second didn't hurt, then it eventually just disappeared. She had other fucked up stuff like tuberculosis type cough that was apparently also fixed. Pretty wild.

It's fun because a lot of it is just very modern and rational-sounding, like they literally use the word "sciatica", talk of inflammation of the kidneys, convulsions, etc., but they also sprinkle in phrases like "tender constitution", "the vaprous secretions of the glands", etc.
